Earlier this afternoon, representatives from Warner Bros. Discovery told NB=
A executives that they would=E2=80=94on the fifth and final day of their ma=
tching rights window=E2=80=94indeed be tendering an offer to match Amazon=
=E2=80=99s $1.8 billion bid for the NBA=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CC=E2=80=9D packa=
ge. I don=E2=80=99t want to equate this endless NBA rights auction with the=
 very significant events currently reshaping our politics and this election=
 cycle, but I will just point out a few facile and obvious similarities her=
e: The seemingly interminable NBA rights auction has also, between fits of =
tedium and unprecedented surprise, been shaped by the disparity between pub=
lic and private conversations, and colored by complex rivalry and personal =
relationships.

Most recently, WBD C.E.O. David Zaslav decided to exercise his matching rig=
hts despite the fact
that many people in the industry and on Wall Street assume that the NBA wou=
ld far prefer to cut a deal with a fresher, pure-play $2 trillion market ca=
p streamer than a debt-saddled legacy media conglomerate. (Even though, as =
my partner Bill Cohan brilliantly noted yesterday, WBD=E2=80=99s debt stack=
 consists of long-dated maturities ( https://puck.news/zazs-everything-on-t=
he-table-era/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Varsity+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F22%2F24%29&ut=
m_content=3DThe+Varsity+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F6%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_a=
ction&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ).)

As I have noted for weeks, the NBA clearly wants to be in business with Ama=
zon, and structured its deal in such a way that it believed WBD couldn=E2=
=80=99t match. Bill Simmons first noted on my partner Matt Belloni=E2=80=99=
s podcast, The Town, that Amazon even offered to put the first three years =
of its contract in escrow immediately. (In its matching rights document, so=
urces say that
WBD included a letter of credit that is able to match this deal point.) =E2=
=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s exceedingly clear that the league is trying to pivot to =
broadcast and digital, and trying to get as far away from cable networks as=
 fast as possible,=E2=80=9D LightShed Partners=E2=80=99 Rich Greenfield tol=
d me late this afternoon, delineating how the NBA is following the NFL=E2=
=80=99s well-worn path.

Elections are usually about a contrast between the past and the future. On =
some level, however, so are modern sports rights media auctions. As was fir=
st evident in the NFL=E2=80=99s most recent rights deals, which kicked off =
last season, and has become increasingly apparent during these NBA negotiat=
ions, sports leagues are focused on nailing the balance between where audie=
nces access their product today (linear TV) and where the next generation i=
s headed (streaming). Some entities, like the now defunct Pac-12, turned do=
wn an Apple TV+ opportunity, in part, because school administrators feared =
that such a
deal would deprive the league of the mass audience it needed to succeed. ML=
S=E2=80=99s exclusive deal with Apple TV+ certainly is transformative=E2=80=
=94but the jury is still out on whether it is transformative for Apple or t=
he MLS. Either way, the desire to manage scale and fees is real and complex=
=2E

One factor that has simplified the process, at least in the past, is the st=
reamers=E2=80=99 willingness to pay handsomely for rights. DirecTV lost mon=
ey on Sunday Ticket for years. But YouTube TV stepped up last year and paid=
 even more (about $2 billion a year) to secure the package starting last se=
ason. Thursday Night Football was a money-loser when Fox carried it for aro=
und $660 million per year. But Amazon came in and paid $1 billion per year =
to pick up those rights. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a clear trend when you wa=
nt to dislodge the established ecosystem,=E2=80=9D Greenfield said. =E2=80=
=9CHow do you get a league to be comfortable with the shift from linear to =
digital? Digital=E2=80=99s got to
flex and use the strength of their balance sheets to overpay. Matching isn=
=E2=80=99t good enough.=E2=80=9D

One senior sports media executive put it even more succinctly to me. =E2=80=
=9CIt=E2=80=99s like the whole chessboard has been shaken up,=E2=80=9D they=
 said. =E2=80=9CNow you have the richest companies in the history of the pl=
anet=E2=80=94ones that have other core competencies=E2=80=94that have decid=
ed to get involved. A billion dollars to Amazon versus a billion dollars to=
 WBD are very different things.=E2=80=9D

And yet, here is Zaslav, attempting to match not only Amazon=E2=80=99s cash=
 but also its reach. The NBA said it=E2=80=99s reviewing WBD=E2=80=99s prop=
osal and offered no timeline for a decision=E2=80=94it could take days; it =
could take weeks. It=E2=80=99s clear that the NBA would rather be in busine=
ss with Amazon, but league executives will pore over the contract to see if=
 WBD has a legitimate claim with its matching rights.

