          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Earlier this aftern=
oon, representatives from Warner Bros. Discovery told NBA executives that t=
hey would=E2=80=94on the <i>fifth</i> and <i>final day </i>of their matchin=
g rights window=E2=80=94indeed be tendering an offer to match Amazon=E2=80=
=99s $1.8 billion bid for the NBA=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CC=E2=80=9D package. I =
don=E2=80=99t want to equate this endless NBA rights auction with the <i>ve=
ry</i> significant events currently reshaping our politics and this electio=
n cycle, but I will just point out a few facile and obvious similarities he=
re: The seemingly <i>interminable</i> NBA rights auction has also, between =
fits of tedium and unprecedented surprise, been shaped by the disparity bet=
ween public and private conversations, and colored by complex rivalry and p=
ersonal relationships.<br/><br/>Most recently, WBD C.E.O. <b>David Zaslav <=
/b>decided to exercise his matching rights despite the fact
that many people in the industry and on Wall Street assume that the NBA wou=
ld far prefer to cut a deal with a fresher, pure-play <i>$2 trillion</i> ma=
rket cap streamer than a debt-saddled legacy media conglomerate. (Even thou=
gh, as my partner <b>Bill Cohan </b>brilliantly noted yesterday, WBD=E2=80=
=99s debt stack consists of <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlb=
WFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dRM1d5aHVuLXNOMG5MUjNPX1Vjcz0iLCJocmVm=
IjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvemF6cy1ldmVyeXRoaW5nLW9uLXRoZS10YWJsZS1lcmEvP3V=
0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1UaGUrVmFyc2l0eSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODclMkYyMiUyRjI0JTI5XH=
UwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9VGhlK1ZhcnNpdHkrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg2JTJGNiUyRjI0J=
TI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVy=
LmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDY=
xN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjo5NjgyMzF9/b1a24a5c2246bf8bb17e99aad0fc24ed9=
3ea955def86ec72e87f544ea92ef077" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:non=
e;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">long-dated maturities</a></u>.) <br/><br/=
>As I have noted for weeks, the NBA clearly wants to be in business with Am=
azon, and structured its deal in such a way that it believed WBD couldn=E2=
=80=99t match. <b>Bill Simmons</b> first noted on my partner <b>Matt Bellon=
i</b>=E2=80=99s podcast, <i>The Town</i>, that Amazon even offered to put t=
he first three years of its contract in escrow immediately. (In its matchin=
g rights document, sources say that
WBD included a letter of credit that is able to match this deal point.) =E2=
=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s exceedingly clear that the league is trying to pivot to =
broadcast and digital, and trying to get as far away from cable networks as=
 fast as possible,=E2=80=9D LightShed Partners=E2=80=99 <b>Rich Greenfield<=
/b> told me late this afternoon, delineating how the NBA is following the N=
FL=E2=80=99s well-worn path. <br/><br/>Elections are usually about a contra=
st between the past and the future. On some level, however, so are modern s=
ports rights media auctions. As was first evident in the NFL=E2=80=99s most=
 recent rights deals, which kicked off last season, and has become increasi=
ngly apparent during these NBA negotiations, sports leagues are focused on =
nailing the balance between where audiences access their product today (lin=
ear TV) and where the next generation is headed (streaming). Some entities,=
 like the now defunct Pac-12, turned down an Apple TV+ opportunity, in part=
, because school administrators feared that such a
deal would deprive the league of the mass audience it needed to succeed. ML=
S=E2=80=99s exclusive deal with Apple TV+ certainly is transformative=E2=80=
=94but the jury is still out on whether it is transformative for Apple or t=
he MLS. Either way, the desire to manage scale and fees is real and complex=
=2E <br/><br/>One factor that has simpl=
ified the process, at least in the pas=
t, is the streamers=E2=80=99 willingness to pay <i>handsomely</i> for right=
s. DirecTV lost money on Sunday Ticket for years. But YouTube TV stepped up=
 last year and paid even more (about $2 billion a year) to secure the packa=
ge starting last season. <i>Thursday Night Football </i>was a money-loser w=
hen Fox carried it for around $660 million per year. But Amazon came in and=
 paid $1 billion per year to pick up those rights. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s=
 a clear trend when you want to dislodge the established ecosystem,=E2=80=
=9D Greenfield said. =E2=80=9CHow do you get a league to be comfortable wit=
h the shift from linear to digital? Digital=E2=80=99s got to
flex and use the strength of their balance sheets to overpay. Matching isn=
=E2=80=99t good enough.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>One senior sports media executive=
 put it even more succinctly to me. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s like the whole ch=
essboard has been shaken up,=E2=80=9D they said. =E2=80=9CNow you have the =
richest companies in the history of the planet=E2=80=94ones that have other=
 core competencies=E2=80=94that have decided to get involved. A billion dol=
lars to Amazon versus a billion dollars to WBD are very different things.=
=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>And yet, here is Zaslav, attempting to match not only Am=
azon=E2=80=99s cash but also its reach. The NBA said it=E2=80=99s reviewing=
 WBD=E2=80=99s proposal and offered no timeline for a decision=E2=80=94it c=
ould take days; it could take weeks. It=E2=80=99s clear that the NBA would =
rather be in business with Amazon, but league executives will pore over the=
 contract to see if WBD has a legitimate claim with its matching rights. <b=
r/></td>
